says that follow. These essays include previously published work by Jean-Pierre Vernant, Pierre Vidal-Naquet, Pietro Pucci, and Charles P. Segal. There also are a new essay by Laura M. Slatkin, two revised and expanded ones by Nancy Felson-Rubin and Michael N. Nagler, and three appearing in English for the first time by Uvo Hlscher, Karl Reinhardt, and Vernant. The result is a collection that juxtaposes older, often hard-to-find articles with significant newer pieces in a way that allows for a fruitful dialogue among them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEpic poetry, GreekxHistory and criticism. 0aOdysseus (Greek mythology) in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAlkinoos.  aMuses.  aNekyia.  aParry, M.  aPorter, H.  aPrometheus.  aSegal, C.  aSiduri.  aSirens.  aTelegony.  aThesprotis.  aVan Nortwick, T.  aWoodhouse, W. J.  aaxis mundi.  aboundaries.  acentrality.  acolonization.  acrying.  adreams.  aeconomics.  aenchantment.  afate.  agifts.  aglory.  ahospitality.  aincest.  ajustice.  akaluptein.  aliminality.  amagic.  anostos.  aoracles.  arealism, of epic.  arites of passage.  aseals.  atemptation.  awarnings.  axenia.1 aFelson-Rubin, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHölscher, Uvo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNagler, Michael N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPucci, Pietro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReinhardt, Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchein, Seth L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchein, Seth L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 